Some patterns are common enough to deserve a one-key shortcut:

  • {key:D} = {key:d}{key:$}
  • {key:C} = {key:c}{key:$}
  • {key:Y} = {key:y}{key:y} *(classic `vi`)* / {key:y}{key:$} *(Neovim default)*
  • {key:S} = {key:c}{key:c}
  • {key:s} = {key:c}{key:l}
  • {key:x} = {key:d}{key:l}
  • {key:X} = {key:d}{key:h}

These are sugar over the grammar. Knowing both forms helps when reading other people's keystrokes — and explains why {key:Y} is a wart (broken symmetry, see [`editing.yank-put`](#editing.yank-put)).
